title: MLAS: rename AVX512BW->AVX512Core
body:
**Description**: Cleanup change: remap functions and files with Avx512BW to Avx512Core.

**Motivation and Context**
The existing processor detection checked for exactly the AVX512BW feature, but all CPUs that have AVX512BW also have AVX512DQ/AVX512VL. It's more convenient to allow all of these instructions now before some additional kernels come online. The Intel compiler and DNNL code call this set of features "core" so that is used here too.

The compiler detection logic in onnxruntime_mlas.cmake has been extended to check for all the flags: any compiler that supported one should support them all.

title: num_dims does not match for input
fix tensor location mismatch in allocation planner
body:
**Description**: This change fixes a rare bug that may cause tensor location mismatch in allocation planner's initialization:

### When does this bug happen?
In `PlannerImpl::CreatePlan()` when initializing a model,
1) if a value **is an initializer**, _and_
2) it is the current graph's **outscope nodearg** (ie. the current graph is not the main graph), _and_
3) it is consumed by at least one OP on CPU EP and one OP on CUDA EP, _and_
4) either of these 2 OP is `If`, `Loop` or `Scan` that consumes the value as implicit input.

### How does this bug happen? 
Take the newly added test case `InferenceSessionTests.Test3LayerNestedSubgraph` as example:

> the main graph has an initializer `data_0`, an `If` operator `graph_0__if_0` and other nodes.
>
> `graph_0__if_0`'s else branch is a subgraph, it contains a `Sub` node and an `If` node. The `Sub` node consumes initializer `data_0` and it will be partitioned on CPU. The `If` node consumes `data_0` as implicit input and it will be partitioned on GPU.
>
> the inner nested `If`'s else branch is a simple subgraph that contains only one node: an `Abs` node that consumes `data_0` as input.

Currently, when initializing graph `graph_0__if_0`'s else branch in PlannerImpl::CreatePlan(), `data_0` will be set location to CPU (because it's input of the `Sub` node) and then will be overwritten to GPU (because it's implicit input of the `If` node).
At runtime, when executing `If` cuda implementation, it will look up its implicit input's location: in this case its location is 'GPU', and it requires GPU because the `Abs` node wants a GPU input. It is a GPU-to-GPU, so it does a no-op in fetching implicit input for `data_0`.
As a result, the `data_0`'s raw data ( a CPU memory address ) will be passed to cuda as a GPU device address, and cause the inference failure ( segfault when GPU-as-CPU, or CUDA failure when CPU-as-GPU).

### Why this is not discovered before
When doing another change (#2942), it failed the model test of `mlperf_ssd_mobilenet_300`. The model is labeled as 'expected to fail', but this change triggered a segfault which failed the whole process.

The issue is hard to reproduce because it requires the 4 conditions to match (see above). If any of the 4 conditions is not fulfilled (it's too difficult to fulfill), the issue will not be trigger. This will almost never happen because it requires an at-least 3-layer nested graph, with an node somehow partitioned onto CPU that consumed the same initializer that another If node will also consume as implicit input. I constructed a 3-layer nested graph to reproduce this issue in the tests.

### About the fix
Currently, `PlannerImpl::CreatePlan()` set an outscope initializer's location to default if it is an operator's implicit input. Correspondingly, in `TransformerMemcpyImpl::ProcessDefs()` implicit inputs are considered its location is default. The problem is, TransformerMemcpy will not work on a node's implicit inputs because implicit inputs are not in the node's NodeArgs list; on the other side the planner may override the location into default (a wrong value in this case).

Skip setting locations to implicit input should be able to resolve this issue.

title: QLinearMatMul speed up
body:
**Description**: The equivalent of PR#3196 but done for QLinearMatMul. Use MLAS to do a u8u8=s32 GEMM and then requantize this intermediate buffer.

**Motivation and Context**
The existing implementation of QLinearMatMul was using gemmlowp without threading and was restricted to SSE4.1. This changes the kernel to instead use MLAS for threading and scalable instruction set.

The requantization is changed from the gemmlowp fixed point strategy to use FP32 instructions, which is simpler on x86/x64. This makes the results not bit identical to the old version: for results near y.499xx, the gemmlowp version would round up to the next integer. The new version rounds this down instead.

This also removes the special SSE 4.1 flag used to compiler gemmlowp for x86/x64 as this code is no longer used on these platforms.

title: Replacing CudaAsyncBuffer with TArray to improve perf
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
Using TArray instead of CudaAsyncBuffer to passing tensor meta data(mostly, tensor strides/pitches) to CUDA kernels to improve performance

**Motivation and Context**
 Basically, with CudaAsyncBuffer, the sequence at host side is like below. 
1. fill meta data to CPU Pinned memory
2. call cudaMemcpyAsync to upload these meta data from CPU Pinned memory to GPU memory.
3. launch CUDA kernel.

On device(GPU) side, the copy in #2 won't be executed until the moment when kernel in #3 is about to run on GPU. Usually, host side runs far ahead of device side. So, it is better to do data uploading early(during kernel launch time) on host side rather than until kernel execution to save time on GPU. To achieve it, we introduced TArray by which the data is passed to CUDA kernels by pass-by-value. On BERT-L training, we saw about 3-5% perf improvement.

Precompute packed representation of B matrix in MatMul, when the matrix is constant

labels.name: status:wontfix
labels.description: This will not be worked on

body:
**Description**: Precompute packed representation of B matrix in MatMul, when the matrix is constant.

**Motivation and Context**

GEMM implementation in MLAS processes right-hand side matrix block by block.
Each block is first copied into a packed buffer for cache locality. When the
matrix is constant, this block packing can be precomputed at load time.

The block dimensions are chosen based on all three matrix dimensions. One of
them (number of rows in the left-hand side matrix) may not be known at load
time. In this case some heuristics are applied to choose the block dimensions.
In rare cases this may be a regression, but in most scenarios we get gains.
(See [the gist][1] for microbenchmarks.) The regression can likely be avoided
if we provide an API that allows specifying the typical range of values for a
symbolic dimension (similar to AddFreeDimensionOverride).

As an example, BERT_Squad model shows 5-9% average latency reduction. Our
production model (based on BERT) gets 20-25% latency and CPU improvement.

This PR implements the optimization for MatMul operator. It can be applied in
future for Gemm operator too.

Implementation notes: we add two 'internal' operations - one for packing the
matrix, another for MatMul with prepacked right-hand side. The first operation
is then precomputed by constant folding pass. It's possible that the same
matrix is involved in multiple MatMul operations. Until [common subexpression
elimination PR][2] is merged, this will lead to duplicated prepacked constants.

[1]: https://gist.github.com/MaximKalininMS/362c857c8c1c9755a3ccc7b1c1ae651f
[2]: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/3047

title: Foward ORT error messages on the C-ABI to exceptions thrown in winml
body:
When layering was done, errors that occur on the c-abi boundary that are wrapped by OrtStatuses were not forwarded properly to winml exceptions, and only the translated HRESULT was surfaced, and not the message.

Fix: When a failing c-abi call is made, the RETURN_HR_IF_NOT_OK_MSG macro needs to set an issue an originateerror call to save the error string at the point of failure. The corresponding throw that occurs downstream needs to reuse that error message when creating the exception. This is done by calling winrt::hresult_error with from_abi_t, which will check to get the error message from there instead of clobbering it.
